            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Flattening is common when moving from a spatial representation into a simple fully connected layer. For example, an image might start with height and width dimensions, but a basic linear layer often expects one long feature vector."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Reshape, squeeze, unsqueeze, and flatten are all examples of structural operations. They usually do not change the numeric values themselves. They change how PyTorch interprets those values across dimensions."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Worked example: shape changes step by step", "content": "x = torch.tensor([1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0])\nprint(x.shape)                # (4,)\nx = x.reshape(2, 2)\nprint(x.shape)                # (2, 2)\nx = x.unsqueeze(0)\nprint(x.shape)                # (1, 2, 2)\nx = x.flatten()\nprint(x.shape)                # (4,)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "A good shape habit is to narrate the meaning of each step. In the example above, the same four values move from a flat vector to a 2x2 matrix, then to a batch of one matrix, then back to a flat vector."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Common shape mistakes", "content": "Using `(n,)` when the code really expects `(n, 1)`, flattening too early, squeezing away a batch dimension by accident, and assuming broadcasting will work without checking dimensions are the most common mistakes."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Recap checkpoint", "items": ["Can you explain the difference between `(3,)`, `(1, 3)`, and `(3, 1)`?", "Can you add and remove singleton dimensions intentionally?", "Can you predict the output shape of a broadcasted add?", "Can you explain what flattening preserves and what it changes?"]},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Shape debugging habit", "content": "When code fails, print the shape before and after each operation. A few `print(x.shape)` lines are often the fastest way to understand what went wrong."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why this chapter matters later", "content": "CNNs, vision models, and transformers all depend heavily on correct dimensions. If shape changes feel mechanical here, later architectures stop looking magical and start looking readable."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Common confusion", "content": "Shape `(3,)` is not the same as shape `(3, 1)` or `(1, 3)`. They contain the same count of values, but they behave differently in matrix multiplication and broadcasting."},
