    {
        "id": "10",
        "number": "11",
        "title": "LSTM Sequence Classifier",
        "lesson": "10_lstm_sequence_classifier",
        "summary": "Learn sequence modeling with token ids, embeddings, LSTM hidden states, and a classifier built from the final sequence summary.",
        "image": "10_lstm_cell.png",
        "script_path": "tutorials/10_lstm_sequence_classifier.py",
        "pdf_path": "tutorials/pdfs/10_lstm_sequence_classifier.pdf",
        "question_ids": [],
        "previous_chapter": "14",
        "next_chapter": "11",
        "sections": [
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This chapter introduces sequence modeling. Unlike images, sequence data has an order, and the model should care about that order. LSTMs are useful to study because they build a strong mental model for ordered data before you move on to transformers."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Pipeline", "items": ["Integer token ids go into an embedding layer.", "Embeddings go into the LSTM.", "The LSTM produces sequence outputs and hidden states.", "A classifier uses the final hidden state to predict one class for the whole sequence."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Model definition", "content": "self.embedding = nn.Embedding(VOCAB_SIZE, 32)\nself.lstm = nn.LSTM(input_size=32, hidden_size=32, batch_first=True)\nself.classifier = nn.Linear(32, 2)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The input starts as token ids of shape `(batch, seq_len)`. Those integers are not rich enough by themselves, so the embedding layer converts each token id into a learned dense vector."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Embedding shape change", "content": "tokens shape: (64, 10)\nembedded = self.embedding(tokens)\nembedded shape: (64, 10, 32)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "An embedding layer is like a learnable lookup table. Every token id maps to one trainable vector. Similar tokens can eventually get similar embeddings if the training problem encourages that."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Embedding Table Shape", "content": "Embedding matrix shape = (vocab_size, embedding_dim)\nHere: (15, 32)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "`batch_first=True` means PyTorch will use shapes `(batch, seq_len, features)` instead of `(seq_len, batch, features)`. That is often easier for beginners to read."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "LSTM outputs", "content": "outputs, (hidden_state, cell_state) = self.lstm(embedded)"},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Returned tensors", "items": ["`outputs` shape `(batch, seq_len, hidden_size)` gives one output per time step.", "`hidden_state` shape `(num_layers, batch, hidden_size)` stores the final hidden state for each layer.", "`cell_state` has the same shape as `hidden_state` and represents the LSTM's internal memory state."]},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Many beginners get stuck because three different tensors come back from the LSTM call. The easiest way to stay clear is to ask: do I want a representation for every position, or one summary for the whole sequence? `outputs` is position-by-position. `hidden_state[-1]` is a whole-sequence summary."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "LSTM Gate Sketch", "content": "f_t = σ(W_f [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_f)\ni_t = σ(W_i [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_i)\no_t = σ(W_o [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_o)\n\\tilde{c}_t = tanh(W_c [h_{t-1}, x_t] + b_c)\nc_t = f_t ⊙ c_{t-1} + i_t ⊙ \\tilde{c}_t\nh_t = o_t ⊙ tanh(c_t)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "You do not need to memorize every gate equation immediately, but the structure is worth seeing once. The forget gate decides what old information to keep, the input gate decides what new information to write, and the output gate decides what part of the memory becomes the visible hidden state."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "In this one-layer LSTM, `hidden_state[-1]` is the last layer's final hidden state, so it has shape `(batch, hidden_size)`. That makes it a convenient summary vector for sequence classification."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Sequence summary for classification", "content": "final_hidden = hidden_state[-1]\nlogits = self.classifier(final_hidden)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The classifier then does exactly the same kind of thing you have seen before in feedforward networks: it maps one feature vector per example into class logits. The new part is how that feature vector was created from an ordered sequence."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The toy labeling rule depends on comparing the later half of the sequence with the earlier half. That means sequence order matters. If you shuffle the same token values into a different order, the label can change."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Toy label rule", "content": "first_half = tokens[:, : SEQ_LEN // 2].float().mean(dim=1)\nsecond_half = tokens[:, SEQ_LEN // 2 :].float().mean(dim=1)\nlabels = (second_half > first_half).long()"},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Label Rule In Math Form", "content": "label = 1 if mean(second half) > mean(first half)\nlabel = 0 otherwise"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That kind of task is exactly what sequence models are for: learn from values across time or position, not just from an unordered bag of numbers."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Notice that a plain average over all tokens would throw away the very information that defines the label here. The model needs some way to preserve the distinction between earlier and later positions, and the recurrent state gives it that mechanism."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Validation prediction", "content": "val_logits = model(val_x)\nval_preds = val_logits.argmax(dim=1)\nval_acc = (val_preds == val_y).float().mean().item()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "As in the multiclass MLP and CNN chapters, the logits are turned into class predictions with `argmax(dim=1)`. The only major difference is that those logits now summarize a whole sequence rather than an image or tabular point."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "outputs vs hidden_state", "content": "`outputs` gives one vector per time step. `hidden_state` gives the final summary state per layer. Beginners often mix them up, so keep the distinction explicit."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "LSTM intuition", "content": "Think of the model as reading tokens one by one, updating an internal memory, and then using its final memory summary to make a class decision."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why this chapter matters", "content": "LSTMs are not the newest dominant sequence model, but they teach durable ideas: embeddings, temporal order, hidden memory, and reducing a whole sequence to one vector for classification."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Recap checkpoint", "items": ["Can you explain why token ids need an embedding layer?", "Can you explain the difference between `outputs` and `hidden_state`?", "Can you explain why `hidden_state[-1]` works as a sequence summary?", "Can you explain why order matters in this toy task?"]},
        ],
    },
    {
        "id": "11",
        "number": "12",
        "title": "Transformer Basics",
        "lesson": "11_transformer_basics",
        "summary": "Build a tiny Transformer encoder classifier and learn embeddings, positional encodings, attention-friendly shapes, and sequence pooling.",
        "image": "11_encoder_self_attention.png",
        "script_path": "tutorials/11_transformer_basics.py",
        "pdf_path": "tutorials/pdfs/11_transformer_basics.pdf",
        "question_ids": [],
        "previous_chapter": "10",
        "next_chapter": "12",
        "sections": [
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This chapter introduces the Transformer encoder using a deliberately small sequence-classification problem. The main goal is not scale. It is to understand the shape flow and the architectural differences from recurrent models like LSTMs."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Pipeline", "items": ["Token ids go into an embedding layer.", "Positional encoding is added so order is visible.", "Transformer encoder layers mix information across positions.", "The sequence is pooled into one vector for classification."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Core model pieces", "content": "self.embedding = nn.Embedding(VOCAB_SIZE, EMBED_DIM)\nself.pos_encoding = PositionalEncoding(EMBED_DIM)\nself.encoder = nn.TransformerEncoder(encoder_layer, num_layers=2)\nself.classifier = nn.Linear(EMBED_DIM, NUM_CLASSES)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The embedding step is familiar from the LSTM chapter. The big architectural difference is what happens next. Instead of processing tokens one by one through recurrence, the Transformer encoder updates token representations by letting positions interact through attention."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Input and embedding shapes", "content": "tokens shape: (64, 8)\nembedded = self.embedding(tokens)\nembedded shape: (64, 8, 32)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Because `batch_first=True` is used in the encoder layer, the model reads shapes as `(batch, seq_len, features)`. That makes it easier to compare this chapter directly with the LSTM chapter."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Embedding Matrix Shape", "content": "Embedding table shape = (vocab_size, embed_dim)\nHere: (20, 32)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Transformers do not know token order by default. If you only gave the model embeddings, it could see which token values are present but not where they occur. Positional encoding solves that problem by adding a position-dependent signal to each token vector."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Positional encoding idea", "content": "x = self.embedding(tokens)\nx = self.pos_encoding(x)\nx = self.encoder(x)"},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Sinusoidal Positional Encoding Sketch", "content": "PE(pos, 2i)   = sin(pos / 10000^(2i / d_model))\nPE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i / d_model))"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "You do not need to memorize the exact sinusoidal formula, but you should remember the purpose: inject position information without changing the token ids themselves. After this addition, token vectors carry both content and position."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The encoder layer then applies self-attention and feedforward blocks. In a high-level sense, each token can look at other tokens in the same sequence and build a richer representation based on context."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Attention Intuition", "content": "Each position builds a weighted combination of other positions.\nThe weights depend on learned compatibility scores between token representations."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That is the key conceptual jump beyond recurrence. In an LSTM, information is passed through a chain over time. In a Transformer encoder, positions can interact more directly within a layer."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Pooling the sequence", "content": "x = self.encoder(x)\npooled = x.mean(dim=1)\nlogits = self.classifier(pooled)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Mean pooling is a simple way to reduce the full sequence into one vector for classification. It keeps the architecture beginner-friendly. Later Transformer models may use a dedicated classification token or more specialized pooling strategies."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Sequence Pooling Shape Rule", "content": "If encoder output shape is (batch, seq_len, d_model),\nthen mean over dim 1 gives shape (batch, d_model)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The synthetic label rule in the script depends on whether the total token sum is large. That makes this a whole-sequence classification task rather than a token-level task."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Toy label rule", "content": "labels = (tokens.sum(dim=1) > (SEQ_LEN * VOCAB_SIZE / 2)).long()"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "Once pooled, the classifier is ordinary multiclass classification again. The model outputs logits of shape `(batch, 2)`, `CrossEntropyLoss` compares them to integer labels, and `argmax(dim=1)` gives predicted classes."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Transformer vs LSTM", "content": "Both models use embeddings and sequence shapes, but the Transformer does not rely on a recurrent hidden state that marches through time. It uses attention-based mixing across positions."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why this chapter matters", "content": "Modern language models are built on Transformer ideas. This tiny encoder is a beginner-sized version of the same family of architectures."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Recap checkpoint", "items": ["Can you explain why Transformers need positional information?", "Can you explain the shape change from token ids to embeddings to pooled sequence vectors?", "Can you explain why mean pooling works for whole-sequence classification?", "Can you explain the conceptual difference between recurrence and attention?"]},
        ],
    },
    {
        "id": "12",
        "number": "13",
        "title": "Toy GAN",
        "lesson": "12_toy_gan",
        "summary": "Learn generator-vs-discriminator training, adversarial losses, and why `detach()` matters in a tiny GAN on a 1D distribution.",
        "image": "12_gan_illustration.png",
        "script_path": "tutorials/12_toy_gan.py",
        "pdf_path": "tutorials/pdfs/12_toy_gan.pdf",
        "question_ids": [],
        "previous_chapter": "11",
        "next_chapter": "13",
        "sections": [
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "GANs are different from the supervised models in earlier chapters because there is no ordinary label per training example. Instead, two networks play opposing roles. The generator tries to create convincing fake samples, and the discriminator tries to tell real samples from fake ones."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Two-network game", "items": ["Generator: maps random noise to fake samples.", "Discriminator: maps a sample to one logit meaning real vs fake.", "Discriminator step: reward correct real/fake judgments.", "Generator step: reward fake samples that fool the discriminator."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Generator and discriminator outputs", "content": "fake_samples = generator(sample_noise(batch_size))\nreal_logits = discriminator(real_samples)\nfake_logits = discriminator(fake_samples)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The dataset here is intentionally tiny and one-dimensional. Real samples come from a Gaussian centered near 2.0. That keeps the focus on adversarial training logic rather than on data complexity."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Real and noise distributions", "content": "real = torch.randn(batch_size, 1) * 0.7 + 2.0\nnoise = torch.randn(batch_size, 3)"},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Generator And Discriminator Shapes", "content": "Noise shape = (batch, 3)\nGenerated sample shape = (batch, 1)\nDiscriminator logit shape = (batch, 1)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The discriminator is trained with `BCEWithLogitsLoss`, just like earlier binary-classification chapters. Real examples get target 1. Fake examples get target 0. So the discriminator is, in one sense, just a binary classifier."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Discriminator targets", "content": "real_targets = torch.ones_like(real_logits)\nfake_targets = torch.zeros_like(fake_logits)\nd_loss = loss_fn(real_logits, real_targets) + loss_fn(fake_logits, fake_targets)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The generator step flips the objective. It wants fake samples to receive discriminator outputs that look real. So it feeds fresh generated samples into the discriminator and compares those logits to a target of 1."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Generator objective", "content": "generated = generator(sample_noise(batch_size))\nfooled_logits = discriminator(generated)\ng_loss = loss_fn(fooled_logits, torch.ones_like(fooled_logits))"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That means the two losses are not independent. Improving one network changes the learning environment of the other. This is what makes GAN training more unstable and more interesting than ordinary supervised learning."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Adversarial Objective Intuition", "content": "Discriminator: maximize ability to separate real from fake\nGenerator: maximize ability to make fake look real"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The `detach()` call during the discriminator step is essential. Without it, gradients from the discriminator's fake-sample loss would flow back into the generator when you are supposed to be updating only the discriminator."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Why detach is needed", "content": "fake_samples = generator(sample_noise(batch_size)).detach()\n# discriminator update should not change generator parameters"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The script prints `fake_mean` as a sanity check. Since real samples are centered near 2.0, a generator that is learning something useful should eventually move its outputs toward that region."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Sanity metric", "content": "samples = generator(sample_noise(1000))\nprint(samples.mean().item())"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This is not a full evaluation metric, but it is a practical beginner-friendly signal. If generated samples stay centered near a completely wrong value, the generator is probably not matching the target distribution yet."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why GANs feel unstable", "content": "The target is moving. The generator is learning against the current discriminator, and the discriminator is learning against the current generator. Both sides keep changing."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "What this chapter teaches well", "content": "Even a toy GAN makes you practice multi-network optimization, alternating updates, `detach()`, and the idea that a loss can come from another learned model rather than from fixed labels."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Recap checkpoint", "items": ["Can you explain the roles of the generator and discriminator?", "Can you explain why the discriminator is still a binary classifier?", "Can you explain why `detach()` is needed during the discriminator step?", "Can you explain why `fake_mean` is a useful sanity check here?"]},
        ],
    },
