            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This chapter adds a plain recurrent neural network as a dedicated lesson. The goal is to understand the simplest recurrent sequence model clearly before or alongside LSTMs and transformers."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Pipeline", "items": ["Token ids go into an embedding layer.", "Embeddings go into a vanilla RNN.", "The RNN updates a hidden state across time.", "The final hidden state is classified into one sequence label."]},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Model definition", "content": "self.embedding = nn.Embedding(VOCAB_SIZE, 32)\nself.rnn = nn.RNN(input_size=32, hidden_size=32, batch_first=True)\nself.classifier = nn.Linear(32, 2)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "A vanilla RNN is the cleanest way to see recurrence. At each time step, the model combines the current token representation with the previous hidden state to produce a new hidden state. That hidden state acts like the running memory of the sequence so far."},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Vanilla RNN Update", "content": "h_t = tanh(W_x x_t + W_h h_{t-1} + b)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The input starts as integer token ids of shape `(batch, seq_len)`. The embedding layer converts those ids into dense vectors, giving shape `(batch, seq_len, embed_dim)`."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Embedding shape change", "content": "tokens shape: (64, 10)\nembedded = self.embedding(tokens)\nembedded shape: (64, 10, 32)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "PyTorch's `nn.RNN` returns two outputs: `outputs` and `hidden_state`. `outputs` contains one vector per time step. `hidden_state` contains the final hidden state for each recurrent layer."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "RNN outputs", "content": "outputs, hidden_state = self.rnn(embedded)"},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Returned tensors", "items": ["`outputs` shape `(batch, seq_len, hidden_size)` gives one vector per position.", "`hidden_state` shape `(num_layers, batch, hidden_size)` stores the final state for each recurrent layer.", "For one layer, `hidden_state[-1]` has shape `(batch, hidden_size)` and is a natural sequence summary."]},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "This lesson uses `hidden_state[-1]` for classification because the task needs one label for the whole sequence rather than one label per token position."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Sequence summary for classification", "content": "final_hidden = hidden_state[-1]\nlogits = self.classifier(final_hidden)"},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "The toy label rule compares the later half of the sequence with the earlier half. That means order matters. The same token values in a different order can lead to a different class label."},
            {"type": "code", "title": "Toy label rule", "content": "first_half = tokens[:, : SEQ_LEN // 2].float().mean(dim=1)\nsecond_half = tokens[:, SEQ_LEN // 2 :].float().mean(dim=1)\nlabels = (second_half > first_half).long()"},
            {"type": "math", "title": "Why RNNs Are Limited", "content": "Repeated recurrence over many steps\ncan make gradients vanish or explode,\nwhich makes long-range memory difficult."},
            {"type": "paragraph", "content": "That limitation is why LSTMs and GRUs were developed. They keep the core recurrent idea but add mechanisms that make it easier to preserve useful information across longer ranges."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "RNN vs LSTM", "content": "A vanilla RNN has only a hidden state. An LSTM adds gates and a cell state to manage memory more carefully across time."},
            {"type": "callout", "title": "Why this chapter matters", "content": "If you understand a plain RNN first, LSTMs look like a refinement of recurrence rather than a completely new idea."},
            {"type": "list", "title": "Recap checkpoint", "items": ["Can you explain how the hidden state changes across time in a vanilla RNN?", "Can you explain the difference between `outputs` and `hidden_state`?", "Can you explain why `hidden_state[-1]` works for sequence classification?", "Can you explain why longer sequences are harder for vanilla RNNs?"]},
